aVDetroit Tigers slugger Miguel Cabrera punched New York Yankees catcher Austin Romine, sparking a brawl during Thursday's game.\u000a\u000aThe fracas was the first of three that led to the ejections of five players, managers Joe Girardi and Brad Ausmus, and Yankees bench coach Rob Thomson, CBS News reported.\u000a\u000aAfter Yankees reliever Tommy Kahnle threw a pitch behind Cabrera, discussion between Cabrera and Romine turned physical with Cabrera shoving the Yankees relief catcher and throwing a swing. The two tumbled to the ground and both benches cleared during the sixth inning. Cabrera and Romine were ejected from the game.\u000a\u000aYankees manager Girardi and Kahnle were ejected before the brawl, ESPN reported. Thomson and Yankees reliever Dellin Betances were ejected in the seventh inning. Tigers manager Ausmus and reliever Alex Wilson were ejected in the eighth inning.\u000a\u000aGirardi complained of a "very poor job" on the part of umpires and an obscenity yelled by Ausmus at Brett Gardner in the eighth inning, ESPN reported.\u000a\u000aYankees catcher Gary Sanchez also could face suspension for his role in the fights.\u000a\u000a"At that moment, instinct takes over," Sanchez told ESPN. "That's your family out there."\u000a\u000aTensions rose in the fifth inning when Tigers pitcher Michael Fulmer hit Gary Sanchez in the thigh with his first pitch, The New York Times noted.\u000a\u000a"I mean, pay attention," Girardi said, criticizing umpire Carlos Torres and the crew chief Dana DeMuth, according to the Times. "Somebody\u2019s got to pay attention to what\u2019s going on in this game."\u000a\u000aThe Tigers won the game 10-6.\u000a\u000aTwitter users commented on the mayhem.\u000a\u000aCabrera vs. Romine looks like what Mayweather vs. McGregor would be like if McG could use his usual style. Push, punch -take down! \u2014 Frank Baker (@EduardusUrsus) August 25, 2017\u000a\u000aI commend Gary Sanchez for throwing a sucker punch at Miguel Cabrera after he swung three times at Romine, that's a teammate you want. \u2014 Hirsty \U0001f1fa\U0001f1f8 (@d_hirsty) August 25, 2017\u000a\u000aCabrera threw a good lookin punch but Romine has obviously been in a few scraps himself. I don't think his brother was worried at all \u2014 Kentucky George \u26be (@catfangeorge) August 25, 2017
p137
aVQantas hopes to schedule the world's longest nonstop flight in commercial travel aviation with a 20-hour flight from Sydney to London \u2014 that is if Boeing or Airbus can actually create a plane that can carry passengers continuously for that long.\u000a\u000aQantas, based in Australia, has promised to add the routes within the next five years, USA Today reported. The airline has already announced a 17-hour, 9,010-mile nonstop flight from Perth to London, making it one of the longest continuous flying routes in the world and the first nonstop from Australia to Europe.\u000a\u000aA source told Reuters that Qantas' Sydney-to-London flight will take a northern polar route on most days rather than the usual western crossing over Asia and Europe.\u000a\u000aThe polar route is longer than the 9,200 nautical miles western route but benefits from a strong tailwinds rather than powerful headwinds on a more direct western route, the wire agency reported.\u000a\u000a"The smart way is not to fight the winds. Use them," Leeham Co analyst Bjorn Fehrm said in a note to clients speculating about a 10,000-nautical-mile polar route in June, Reuters noted.\u000a\u000aThe Qantas planes would greatly expand the capabilities of commercial airlines flying nonstop. Emirates currently has the distinction of having the longest nonstop flight by distance, with its daily flight to Auckland, New Zealand, taking 16 hours outbound and 17 hours and 15 minutes on the return flight, according to CNN.\u000a\u000aThe longest current route in relationship to distance is the Air India flight to San Francisco, which travels 9,408 miles, via a Pacific Ocean route rather than the polar route it used to take, according to CNN. The network stated that the new route takes advantage of high-altitude jet stream, giving it a tailwind boost all the way to San Francisco.\u000a\u000aThat means while it takes about 1,000 more miles to fly, the trip actually shaves two hours off the journey at 15 hours.
p138
aVFirst lady Melania Trump sent a tweet Friday urging those in the path of Hurricane Harvey to be safe.\u000a\u000aShe said that the whole country is sending "thoughts and prayers" to them.\u000a\u000aFor those living near the path of #HurricaneHarvey stay safe! Thoughts & prayers of an entire country are with you. \u2014 Melania Trump (@FLOTUS) August 25, 2017\u000a\u000aThe hurricane was set to hit land late Friday in the middle of the Texas coast, in Corpus Christi.\u000a\u000aHurricane Harvey gained strength on Friday, potentially becoming the strongest hurricane to hit the U.S. in 12 years.
