aVLeBron James defended Isaiah Thomas and slammed fans for burning jerseys on Thursday.\u000a\u000aThe NBA star shamed Boston Celtic fans on Twitter for setting fire to their Thomas jerseys after the player was traded for Kyrie Irving.\u000a\u000a"The burning of the jersey thing is getting ridiculous now!" LeBron posted, reminding fans that Isiah had been traded before proceeding to remind them of the death of the player\u2019s sister.\u000a\u000aThe burning of the jersey thing is getting ridiculous now! The man was traded. What do u not understand? & played in a game after ..... \u2014 LeBron James (@KingJames) August 24, 2017\u000a\u000asister tragic death. Gordon Hayward paid he's dues as well and decided to do what's best for him and family. Put in the work, got better.... \u2014 LeBron James (@KingJames) August 24, 2017\u000a\u000aBecame an All-Star, etc!! If these guys weren't good, u guys would be the first to say "get them up out of here". Man beat it! When "we".... \u2014 LeBron James (@KingJames) August 24, 2017\u000a\u000adecide to do what best for us it's "cowardly" "traitor", etc but when it's on the other side it's "business" huh!?!? Ooh ok. Man do..... \u2014 LeBron James (@KingJames) August 24, 2017\u000a\u000awhat u feel is best for your profession, love, family, happiness and continue to #StriveForGreatness\U0001f680 #Salute \u2014 LeBron James (@KingJames) August 24, 2017\u000a\u000aJames was not the only one to comment on the issue and was joined by other players determined to have their say on social media.\u000a\u000aResponding to a video posted by a fan on Twitter, in which a Thomas jersey is set alight, Celitcs player Jaylen Brown said it was "pathetic."\u000a\u000aThis is pathetic https://t.co/ldJ4Mypd0q \u2014 Jaylen Brown (@FCHWPO) August 24, 2017\u000a\u000aThe Cleveland Cavaliers traded with The Celtics on Tuesday, after Irving requested he be transferred.\u000a\u000aESPN noted that, at the time, the all-star point guard cited wanting to be in a situation where he was more of a focal point.\u000a\u000aHe also listed not wanting to play alongside James, as motivation for the trade.\u000a\u000aThomas is yet to comment about the switch however, NBA insider Chris Broussard revealed that his Boston teammates "weren\u2019t really fond of him," NESN reported.\u000a\u000a"We know he had those problems in Sacramento and in Phoenix. I didn\u2019t know he was having those issues \u2014 before (talking with) these executives \u2014 in Boston," Broussard said.\u000a\u000aHowever, many players have since come out in defense of Thomas and dismissing these claims.\u000a\u000aFormer teammate Evan Turner told CelticsBlog that Thomas was "the type of person to more so be hurt if someone wasn't giving their all because that little dude battles."\u2019\u000a\u000aHe added it was unreal to see Thomas rise above.\u000a\u000a"Nothing ill should ever be said about that guy. He's maximizing everything he's been blessed with on and off the court."
