aVSome Americans are misguidedly tearing down the United States, focusing too much on its imperfect history and forgetting its greatness, Michael Reagan, the son of President Ronald Reagan, told Newsmax TV on Wednesday.\u000a\u000aReagan was asked about his reaction to the decision by Baltimore Mayor Catherine Pugh to remove all Confederate moments from public spaces following the deadly white power rally in Charlottesville, by Miranda Khan on Newsmax's "America Talks Now."\u000a\u000a"It was her decision to make but I believe it was made because of the fear of riots in Baltimore and statues being torn down as they were last night in other cities back in the east coast. So it's really out of fear at this point and time.\u000a\u000a"It's really unfortunate to the point that I think most of these people who are acting and reacting like this have never studied the history of the United States, really study it, study who these people are.\u000a\u000a"I doubt if any of them know how to spell the names of the people on the statue and it just shows what's happened with our education system in America. We're raising people to hate parts of America instead of raising people to find ways to love parts of America."\u000a\u000aImportant: Newsmax TV is available on DirecTV Ch. 349, U-Verse 1220, and FiOS 615. If your cable operator does not have Newsmax TV just call and ask them to put us on \u2013 Call toll-free 1-844-500-6397 and we will connect you right away to your cable operator!\u000a\u000aFor more places to Find Newsmax TV \u2013 Click Here Now\u000a\u000aAmong the statues pulled down in the dead of night because of their connections to slavery were the Robert E. Lee and Stonewall Jackson Monument and the Confederate Soldiers and Sailors Monument, The New York Times reported.\u000a\u000a"The fact is we've changed over the years. That is part of our history. And if we keep on tearing down our history what will our history be?" Reagan told Khan.\u000a\u000a"The problem with the media today is they believe history began this morning when they woke up. And that's sad that we've done that.\u000a\u000a"I remember playing golf with a young man a couple of years ago when I was headed to Normandy to raise the American flag at the American cemetery at Normandy. A 28-year-old young man looked at me and didn't know why there was an American cemetery at Normandy."\u000a\u000aAnd during a trip to Germany, Reagan added, "a kid I ran into in Berlin... thought the Americans put up the Berlin Wall to keep the communists out of their sector."\u000a\u000a"We sit there and we don't educate people on what's great about America," he said. "We try to find those areas of America that maybe we don't agree with and then you see what's happening in the country and the world today where we grow up angry, mad and what have you. It's truly unfortunate."\u000a\u000aReagan is the author of "Lessons My Father Taught Me: The Strength, Integrity, and Faith of Ronald Reagan," published by Humanix.
